    "input": "What should happen before context compaction if exact tool outputs are still only in the chat?",
    "output": "Before a context compaction operation triggers, you should **move the raw, verbatim tool outputs into a durable persistence layer** (e.g., a database, file\u2011system, or your platform\u2019s long\u2011term\u2011memory store).  \nThe concrete steps are:\n\n| Schritt | Aktion | Ziel |\n|---------|--------|------|\n| 1 | **Capture** the raw output from the tool invocation. | Ensure you have the unaltered, trusted text. |\n| 2 | **Persist** it immediately using `memory_add` (or your platform\u2019s equivalent). | Guarantees that the output survives any subsequent pruning of the chat buffer. |\n| 3 | **Index** or tag the stored record with a unique identifier (e.g., a hash of the tool name + timestamp). | Makes later retrieval and cross\u2011reference easy. |\n| 4 | **Reference** the stored record in the chat (e.g., \u201cSee stored record #12345\u201d). | Keeps the chat concise while pointing to the archived evidence. |\n| 5 | **Verify** that the persistence medium is durable and not part of the compacted segment (e.g., separate DB collection). | Confirms it won\u2019t be lost during compaction. |\n\n**Practical example (pseudo\u2011code):**\n\n```python\noutput = run_tool(...)          # raw tool result\nrecord_id = memory_add(content=output, fact_type=\"tool_output\")\n\n# In the chat\nprint(f\"Tool result archived as record #{record_id}.\")\n```\n\nWith this pattern in place, any future querying (using `memory_search` or manual lookup) will recover the exact tool output, even after the chat history has been compressed. This satisfies the project memory requirement that \u201cexact tool outputs and decisions should be archived as verbatim evidence\u201d before any context compaction.",
